04716nam a22006495i 9780226364025DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263640257 a10.7208/97802263640252doi  a(DE-B1597)525071  a(OCoLC)956377205  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aE185.86b.D73 2017 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.388960732231 aDrake, Simone C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhen We Imagine Grace :bBlack Men and Subject Making /cSimone C. Drake. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b21 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPREFACE. When Crisis Meets Grace -- tAcknowledgments -- tNTRODUCTION. Navigating Discourses of Crisis -- t1. A Friend of My Mind, or Where I Enter -- t2. Nat Love: A New Negro Rebel in Wide Open Spaces -- t3. Lest We Forget: Stories My Grandfather Told Me -- t4. Deliver Us from Evil: Black Family Hauntings in a Neoliberal State -- t5. Twisted Criminalities: Contradictory Black Heroism -- t6. "I'm Not a Businessman, I'm a Business, Man": A Hip- Hop Genealogy of Black Entrepreneurship -- tEpilogue: Black Boys Making Sense of Race -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSimone C. Drake spent the first several decades of her life learning how to love and protect herself, a black woman, from the systems designed to facilitate her harm and marginalization. But when she gave birth to the first of her three sons, she quickly learned that black boys would need protection from these very same systems-systems dead set on the static, homogenous representations of black masculinity perpetuated in the media and our cultural discourse. In When We Imagine Grace, Drake borrows from Toni Morrison's Beloved to bring imagination to the center of black masculinity studies-allowing individual black men to exempt themselves and their fates from a hateful, ignorant society and open themselves up as active agents at the center of their own stories. Against a backdrop of crisis, Drake brings forth the narratives of black men who have imagined grace for themselves. We meet African American cowboy, Nat Love, and Drake's own grandfather, who served in the first black military unit to fight in World War II. Synthesizing black feminist and black masculinity studies, Drake analyzes black fathers and daughters, the valorization of black criminals, the black entrepreneurial pursuits of Marcus Garvey, Berry Gordy, and Jay-Z, and the denigration and celebration of gay black men: Cornelius Eady, Antoine Dodson, and Kehinde Wiley. With a powerful command of its subjects and a passionate dedication to hope, When We Imagine Grace gives us a new way of seeing and knowing black masculinity-sophisticated in concept and bracingly vivid in telling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican American menxSocial conditions. 4aagency. 4ablack culture. 4ablack feminism. 4ablack male crisis. 4ablack masculinity. 4aimagination. 4aintersectionality. 4alaw. 4asubjectivity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226364025423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226364025.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-